    <Folder>
      <name>1-Ctvrtek</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>01-Osterfeuer Freiwillige Feuerwehr Moorwerder</name>
        <description><![CDATA[1st Easter fire in Moorwerder<br>Anyone who wants to get in the mood for Easter on Thursday can be there on Maundy Thursday, March 28th from 7:30 p.m. when the Easter fire is lit in Moorwerder. The Easter fire, where there will also be something to nibble on, will take place on the meadow by the Moorwerder fire station, Bauernstegel 2, 21109 Hamburg . The volunteer fire department definitely knows what it's doing - no one needs to be afraid of the sparks here!]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1899-FFEA00</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            10.0533867,53.4793357,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Port of Hamburg</name>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1899-0288D1-nodesc</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            9.9679233,53.5070965,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
    </Folder>
    <Folder>
      <name>unesco</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Historic Centre of the City of Salzburg</name>
        <description><![CDATA[unique_number: 927<br>id_no: 784<br>rev_bis: <br>short_description_en: <p>Salzburg has managed to preserve an extraordinarily rich urban fabric, developed over the period from the Middle Ages to the 19th century when it was a city-state ruled by a prince-archbishop. Its Flamboyant Gothic art attracted many craftsmen and artists before the city became even better known through the work of the Italian architects Vincenzo Scamozzi and Santini Solari, to whom the centre of Salzburg owes much of its Baroque appearance. This meeting-point of northern and southern Europe perhaps sparked the genius of Salzburg&rsquo;s most famous son, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, whose name has been associated with the city ever since.</p><br>justification_en: <p>The Committee decided to inscribe the nominated property on the basis of cultural <em>criteria (ii), (iv) and (vi)</em> and considered that the site is of outstanding universal value being an important example of a European ecclesiastical city- state which preserves to a remarkable degree its dramatic townscape, its historically significant urban fabric and a large number of outstanding ecclesiastical and secular buildings from several centuries. It is also noteworthy for its associations with the arts, and in particular with music in the person of its famous son, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart.</p><br>date_inscribed: 1996<br>longitude: 13.04333333<br>latitude: 47.80055556<br>area_hectares: 236<br>category: Cultural<br>category_short: C<br>states_name_en: Austria<br>region_en: Europe and North America<br>iso_code: at<br>transboundary: 0]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-seq2-1-0-FFEA00</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="unique_number">
            <value>927.0</value>
          </Data>
          <Data name="id_no">
            <value>784.0</value>
          </Data>
          <Data name="rev_bis">
            <value/>
          </Data>
          <Data name="short_description_en">
            <value><![CDATA[<p>Salzburg has managed to preserve an extraordinarily rich urban fabric, developed over the period from the Middle Ages to the 19th century when it was a city-state ruled by a prince-archbishop. Its Flamboyant Gothic art attracted many craftsmen and artists before the city became even better known through the work of the Italian architects Vincenzo Scamozzi and Santini Solari, to whom the centre of Salzburg owes much of its Baroque appearance. This meeting-point of northern and southern Europe perhaps sparked the genius of Salzburg&rsquo;s most famous son, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, whose name has been associated with the city ever since.</p>]]></value>
          </Data>
          <Data name="justification_en">
            <value><![CDATA[<p>The Committee decided to inscribe the nominated property on the basis of cultural <em>criteria (ii), (iv) and (vi)</em> and considered that the site is of outstanding universal value being an important example of a European ecclesiastical city- state which preserves to a remarkable degree its dramatic townscape, its historically significant urban fabric and a large number of outstanding ecclesiastical and secular buildings from several centuries. It is also noteworthy for its associations with the arts, and in particular with music in the person of its famous son, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart.</p>]]></value>
          </Data>
          <Data name="date_inscribed">
            <value>1996.0</value>
          </Data>
          <Data name="longitude">
            <value>13.04333333</value>
          </Data>
