      <Placemark>
        <name>Wachau Cultural Landscape</name>
        <description><![CDATA[unique_number: 1134<br>id_no: 970<br>rev_bis: <br>short_description_en: <p>The Wachau is a stretch of the Danube Valley between Melk and Krems, a landscape of high visual quality. It preserves in an intact and visible form many traces - in terms of architecture, (monasteries, castles, ruins), urban design, (towns and villages), and agricultural use, principally for the cultivation of vines - of its evolution since prehistoric times.</p><br>justification_en: <p><em>Criterion (ii):</em> The Wachau is an outstanding example of a riverine landscape bordered by mountains in which material evidence of its long historical evolution has survived to a remarkable degree.</p><br><p><em>Criterion (iv):</em> The architecture, the human settlements, and the agricultural use of the land in the Wachau vividly illustrate a basically medieval landscape which has evolved organically and harmoniously over time.</p><br>date_inscribed: 2000<br>longitude: 15.43416667<br>latitude: 48.36444444<br>area_hectares: 18387<br>category: Cultural<br>category_short: C<br>states_name_en: Austria<br>region_en: Europe and North America<br>iso_code: at<br>transboundary: 0]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-seq2-1-5-FFEA00</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
