      <Placemark>
        <name>Tugendhat Villa in Brno</name>
        <description><![CDATA[unique_number: 1226<br>id_no: 1052<br>rev_bis: <br>short_description_en: <p>The Tugendhat Villa in Brno, designed by the architect Mies van der Rohe, is an outstanding example of the international style in the modern movement in architecture as it developed in Europe in the 1920s. Its particular value lies in the application of innovative spatial and aesthetic concepts that aim to satisfy new lifestyle needs by taking advantage of the opportunities afforded by modern industrial production.</p><br>justification_en: <p><em>Criterion (i):</em> The Tugendhat Villa is a masterpiece of the Modern Movement in architecture.</p><br><p><em>Criterion (ii):</em> The German architect Mies van der Rohe applied the radical new concepts of the Modern Movement triumphantly to the Tugendhat Villa to the design of residential buildings.</p><br><p><em>Criterion (iv):</em> Architecture was revolutionized by the Modern Movement in the 1920s and the work of Mies van der Rohe, epitomized by the Tugendhat Villa, played a major role in its worldwide diffusion and acceptance.</p><br>date_inscribed: 2001<br>longitude: 16.61605556<br>latitude: 49.20718333<br>area_hectares: 0.73<br>category: Cultural<br>category_short: C<br>states_name_en: Czechia<br>region_en: Europe and North America<br>iso_code: cz<br>transboundary: 0]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-seq2-1-18-FFEA00</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="unique_number">
            <value>1226.0</value>
          </Data>
          <Data name="id_no">
            <value>1052.0</value>
          </Data>
          <Data name="rev_bis">
            <value/>
          </Data>
          <Data name="short_description_en">
            <value><![CDATA[<p>The Tugendhat Villa in Brno, designed by the architect Mies van der Rohe, is an outstanding example of the international style in the modern movement in architecture as it developed in Europe in the 1920s. Its particular value lies in the application of innovative spatial and aesthetic concepts that aim to satisfy new lifestyle needs by taking advantage of the opportunities afforded by modern industrial production.</p>]]></value>
          </Data>
          <Data name="justification_en">
            <value><![CDATA[<p><em>Criterion (i):</em> The Tugendhat Villa is a masterpiece of the Modern Movement in architecture.</p>
<p><em>Criterion (ii):</em> The German architect Mies van der Rohe applied the radical new concepts of the Modern Movement triumphantly to the Tugendhat Villa to the design of residential buildings.</p>
<p><em>Criterion (iv):</em> Architecture was revolutionized by the Modern Movement in the 1920s and the work of Mies van der Rohe, epitomized by the Tugendhat Villa, played a major role in its worldwide diffusion and acceptance.</p>]]></value>
