      <Placemark>
        <name>Benedictine Convent of St John at Müstair</name>
        <description><![CDATA[unique_number: 299<br>id_no: 269<br>rev_bis: <br>short_description_en: <p>The Convent of Müstair, which stands in a valley in the Grisons, is a good example of Christian monastic renovation during the Carolingian period. It has Switzerland's greatest series of figurative murals, painted c. A.D. 800, along with Romanesque frescoes and stuccoes.</p><br>justification_en: <br>date_inscribed: 1983<br>longitude: 10.44765<br>latitude: 46.62945<br>area_hectares: 2.036<br>category: Cultural<br>category_short: C<br>states_name_en: Switzerland<br>region_en: Europe and North America<br>iso_code: ch<br>transboundary: 0]]></description>
