      <Placemark>
        <name>Three Castles, Defensive Wall and Ramparts of the Market-Town of Bellinzona</name>
        <description><![CDATA[unique_number: 2572<br>id_no: 884<br>rev_bis: <br>short_description_en: <p>The Bellinzona site consists of a group of fortifications grouped around the castle of Castelgrande, which stands on a rocky peak looking out over the entire Ticino valley. Running from the castle, a series of fortified walls protect the ancient town and block the passage through the valley. A second castle (Montebello) forms an integral part of the fortifications, while a third but separate castle (Sasso Corbaro) was built on an isolated rocky promontory south-east of the other fortifications.</p><br>justification_en: <p><em>Criterion (iv):</em> The fortified ensemble of Bellinzona is an outstanding example of a late medieval defensive structure guarding a key strategic Alpine pass.</p><br>date_inscribed: 2000<br>longitude: 9.02242<br>latitude: 46.19314<br>area_hectares: 14.698<br>category: Cultural<br>category_short: C<br>states_name_en: Switzerland<br>region_en: Europe and North America<br>iso_code: ch<br>transboundary: 0]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-seq2-1-99-FFEA00</styleUrl>
